69
00:05:37,903 --> 00:05:40,806
The second challenge was, how can I be involved?

70
00:05:44,156 --> 00:05:53,684
I made this pipeline comparison to figure out the similarities and differences of the character pipeline of Remedy and costume pipeline in live arts, which I'm familiar with.

71
00:05:54,965 --> 00:06:05,013
These processes of either fields are not as linear and defined as it might appear in these charts, but I simplified them for the research sake.

72
00:06:06,434 --> 00:06:11,358
First of all, what I found out was that the pre-productions of these two are very alike.

73
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:15,342
The pre-production starts with analysing the narrative,

74
00:06:15,542 --> 00:06:18,104
whether it is a script or a character bio.

75
00:06:19,105 --> 00:06:22,588
After the script analysis, there are the stages of research,

76
00:06:22,848 --> 00:06:26,470
reference material search, and reference or mood boards,

77
00:06:26,951 --> 00:06:28,952
all identical in both pipelines.

78
00:06:29,893 --> 00:06:32,355
This all leads to visualising the character

79
00:06:32,455 --> 00:06:34,576
in a costume illustration or concept.

80
00:06:36,798 --> 00:06:39,640
The production phases, on the other hand, are very different.

81
00:06:41,153 --> 00:06:43,916
The production of a game character was all new for me,

82
00:06:44,076 --> 00:06:46,859
and I had to figure out how to contribute

83
00:06:47,059 --> 00:06:48,381
to this part of the process.

84
00:06:49,822 --> 00:06:52,385
What was also new were the technical restrictions

85
00:06:52,465 --> 00:06:54,767
of character production that sets frames

86
00:06:54,887 --> 00:06:57,990
to what type of clothing I can design for the characters.

87
00:07:01,033 --> 00:07:03,756
Also, the iteration loops formed a major difference.

88
00:07:04,714 --> 00:07:08,536
During control, sometimes the costume passed through the production phase,

89
00:07:08,716 --> 00:07:13,097
and after testing, ended up all the way back to my desk for a redesign.

90
00:07:13,657 --> 00:07:19,079
While in live arts, the iteration rotates mostly between rehearsals and costume adjustments.

91
00:07:23,001 --> 00:07:26,642
In the end, I was involved with the entire character pipeline of Control.

92
00:07:27,563 --> 00:07:33,165
I worked as part of the character artist's team under the direction of the lead character artist Antti Puomia.

93
00:07:34,626 --> 00:07:40,513
In the pre-production I worked on the character analysis, research, reference boards and costume-based character concepts.

94
00:07:41,214 --> 00:07:47,522
Some new methods were integrated into the pipeline such as stress code and detail boards, but I'll talk about these later on.

95
00:07:49,025 --> 00:07:55,990
During production, I searched for both real and digital textile and clothing material for photo scan and reference purposes.

96
00:07:56,970 --> 00:08:00,072
Character photo suits was a method adapted from live arts.

