00:21:16,110 --> 00:21:17,991
I designed this outfit to emphasize

230
00:21:18,031 --> 00:21:20,812
the brutalistic architecture of the oldest house.

231
00:21:21,313 --> 00:21:23,874
I thought of it as the building in a costume form.

232
00:21:26,835 --> 00:21:29,437
After the concept, I proceeded into detail board

233
00:21:29,597 --> 00:21:30,717
for character artists.

234
00:21:31,458 --> 00:21:33,279
It is meant to give the character artists all

235
00:21:33,299 --> 00:21:35,440
the costume-related information they need,

236
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:38,841
such as material volumes, attachment details,

237
00:21:39,062 --> 00:21:40,162
and the outfit layers.

238
00:21:43,274 --> 00:21:47,918
Here is another detail board example and another one of Jesse's outfit options.

239
00:21:48,678 --> 00:21:53,162
The difference to the previous one is that the concept here is not by me, but by Ville

240
00:21:53,202 --> 00:21:53,622
Kinnunen.

241
00:21:54,998 --> 00:21:58,702
One of my tasks was to define concept artists' character concepts,

242
00:21:59,143 --> 00:22:02,306
since the construction of the costumes they represented

243
00:22:02,406 --> 00:22:03,848
were not always exact.

244
00:22:05,029 --> 00:22:08,113
I translated the concept into seams or layers of clothing

245
00:22:08,673 --> 00:22:12,578
and defined the attachments, materials and other details of the outfit

246
00:22:12,678 --> 00:22:14,780
by paint over and photo reference.

247
00:22:15,901 --> 00:22:19,543
I solved the questions of how to wear it and can the character move in it.

248
00:22:20,443 --> 00:22:23,165
The costumes needed to be realistic and make sense.

249
00:22:23,865 --> 00:22:27,267
Also a narrative connection was created. The costume needed a function.

250
00:22:30,568 --> 00:22:34,030
After the detail boards I created the costumes in Marvelous Designer.

251
00:22:34,870 --> 00:22:41,073
The program is perfect for design communication since it is based on actual clothes manufacturer that I'm familiar with.

252
00:22:42,447 --> 00:22:47,129
So to support character artists' work, I produce either live clothing for Photoscan

253
00:22:47,690 --> 00:22:52,832
or digital clothing in Marvellous Designer. Detail boards were made for the more complex

254
00:22:52,912 --> 00:22:58,354
costumes that were not manufactured in reality. All the actually manufactured

255
00:22:58,414 --> 00:23:01,696
costumes function as detail references themselves.

256
00:23:03,630 --> 00:23:06,210
During production, I sat at the character artist's room

257
00:23:06,291 --> 00:23:08,231
and had a rack of clothes next to my desk.

258
00:23:08,631 --> 00:23:11,052
So we could go through costume construction details

259
00:23:11,092 --> 00:23:12,953
with live clothing when necessary.

260
00:23:13,913 --> 00:23:16,034
I also prepared textures by photographing

261
00:23:16,094 --> 00:23:17,734
and tiling textile materials.

262
00:23:19,935 --> 00:23:23,676
And here is the final 3D model by Daniel Garcia.

263
00:23:27,397 --> 00:23:29,318
Then we have our last example,

264
00:23:30,058 --> 00:23:31,778
the pipeline of live action.

265
00:23:35,563 --> 00:23:43,746
I'm starting with this reference board again to emphasise that the starting point for each costume, whether digital or real, is always the same.

266
00:23:45,066 --> 00:23:48,987
Here is the exploration for Dr Darling based on his character bio.

267
00:23:50,427 --> 00:24:02,911
Darling's character pipeline followed the costume production of Live Arts. I purposefully chose materials hard to render because we didn't have to care about the 3D model this time. This costume only appears in live footage.

268
00:24:06,350 --> 00:24:11,352
At first I bought and put together the wardrobe of Dr. Darling based on the reference board.

269
00:24:12,012 --> 00:24:17,495
Then I photographed each of the outfit variations and defined how is he wearing them and what does

270
00:24:17,575 --> 00:24:25,538
it tell of the character and the situation. Then I made the script analysis and scene breakdown

271
00:24:25,658 --> 00:24:30,901
and decided which outfit he will be wearing in each scene and how is he wearing it.

272
00:24:34,102 --> 00:24:35,383
And then we had the shoots.

273
00:24:37,096 --> 00:24:39,718
On the left, Sam is directing Matthew Perretta,

274
00:24:39,778 --> 00:24:42,261
who plays Dr. Darling, and on the right,

275
00:24:42,501 --> 00:24:44,302
shots of how it looks in the game.

276
00:24:48,366 --> 00:24:49,867
And that was my last example.

277
00:24:50,007 --> 00:24:51,248
It's time to summarize.

278
00:24:52,229 --> 00:24:54,571
I have shown three ways of how Costume Designer

279
00:24:54,611 --> 00:24:57,254
has contributed to the game development of Control,

280
00:24:57,854 --> 00:25:00,817
from developing a protagonist to helping the production,

281
00:25:00,977 --> 00:25:03,159
and finally, live action shoots.

282
00:25:05,642 --> 00:25:13,465
What comes to characters' appearance, people who design characters for games are doing the same thing as costume designers, but digitally.

283
00:25:15,606 --> 00:25:25,470
In Control, I got to do both. I used live arts costume design practices and digital methods to develop realistic characters and support game developers' work.

284
00:25:29,135 --> 00:25:34,685
Last year I started lecturing about digital costume in various costume study programs in Finland

285
00:25:35,346 --> 00:25:40,054
and Aalto University has started integrating digital methods into the costume degree.

286
00:25:41,291 --> 00:25:46,656
In addition to preparing costume designers to work on the digital characters in film and animation,

287
00:25:47,277 --> 00:25:55,884
the aim is to provide future costume designers skills that allow them to offer costume support in game development and other digital productions.

288
00:25:57,085 --> 00:25:59,047
So, let's collaborate!

289
00:26:01,329 --> 00:26:01,650
Thank you!

290
00:26:11,981 --> 00:26:17,165
Instead of taking the questions here, I would like to continue the session in one of the wrap-up rooms,

291
00:26:17,665 --> 00:26:23,229
and I actually have a request for you. I'm looking to continue my research, and since I only have

292
00:26:24,009 --> 00:26:29,413
experience from one company and one project, I would love to hear examples from the industry,

293
00:26:29,613 --> 00:26:33,656
like other examples. Who are the costume responsible people of your company,

294
00:26:33,856 --> 00:26:37,038
and what is the role of costume in your character pipelines?

295
00:26:38,199 --> 00:26:44,184
I'm aware of the collaborations between costume designers and game industry in LA Noire and GTA V,

296
00:26:44,564 --> 00:26:49,709
but I would love to hear more. So if you would like to share any costume related information,

297
00:26:49,829 --> 00:26:53,712
please contact me through the email or join me to the wrap-up room

298
00:26:54,192 --> 00:26:59,196
just across the hall where I'll also answer the questions. Thank you.

